{While strengthening White's center, the typical knight exchange on c3 also
solves most of Black's problems of coordination caused by his relative lack of
space. This explains why there are many systems in which White aims building
up a comparatively modest center (with pawns on d4 and e3 or e2, but without a
pawn on c3) avoiding any early minor piece exchange.Not being under immediate
pressure, Black has a wide range of plans at his disposal, but this freedom
must be handled carefully for if he delays concrete action, he may well be
left in a passive position without counterplay. Mainly, Black can choose
between setting up piece pressure without early pawn breaks, or else prepare
the typical ...e7-e5 break and, slightly less usual, ...c7-c5 (or ...c6-c5.
***The next game illustrates the first situation:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Qb3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 Nc6 {[#]} 8. Nf3 ({This is not
consequent as it allows a minor piece exchange, giving up the bishops pair at
the same time. Better is} 8. Be2 {when Black could use the given tempo for
starting queenside counterplay with} a5 {. Compare with the Spassov-Tukmakov
below.}) 8... Na5 9. Qb4 Nxc4 10. Qxc4 c6 11. Be5 {Aiming at keeping at least
one bishop, as Black was threatening ...Nh5.} Bg4 {The start of Black's piece
play more or less forcing the knight weakening the control over the central
squares.} 12. Nd2 Be6 13. Qe2 Rc8 {[#]} 14. e4 $2 {White does not admit having
lost any chances for an advantage and takes measures against ...c6-c5 which
would at least equalize. But his center becomes vulnerable now.} Bh6 {
Imeadiately occupying the offered diagonal and unpinning the knight. The
immediate threat is ...Ng4 so White needs defending the d4-square.} 15. Nf3 ({
This admits that the knight has just lost time, but} 15. Nb3 Nd7 16. Bg3 Bg7
17. Rd1 Bxb3 18. axb3 Qb6 $17 {wins a pawn.}) 15... b5 $1 {Preventing the
castle due to ...Bc4.} 16. Qc2 ({Another loss of time but} 16. b3 {offers
Black a strong initiative after} Nd7 17. Bg3 Qa5 18. Qc2 c5 19. d5 Bg4 20. O-O
Bg7 21. Rac1 c4 $17) 16... Bg4 17. O-O Nh5 {[#]The fluence of Black's play is
very nice.} 18. Ne2 Qd7 19. Qd3 $6 ({The queen is exposed on this square.
Kortschnoj recommends} 19. Qc3 {but Black is doing great after} f6 20. Bg3 a5 {
combining the positional threats ... a5-a4, ...c6-c5 and ...Nxg3.}) {[#]} 19...
c5 $1 {Pulverizing White's center and yielding Black strong initiative.} 20.
Rad1 (20. d5 {fails to stabilize the positon after} f5 $17) 20... c4 21. Qc3 f5
$1 $17 {Causing the chronical weakening of White's center and kingside. Little
wonder than in the game he will go down quickly.} 22. exf5 Rxf5 23. Ng3 Rf7 24.
Nxh5 $6 {Weakening the king's defense.} Bxh5 25. d5 Rcf8 26. Qd4 Rxf3 $1 27.
gxf3 Qh3 0-1

