{For White, an effective plan could be starting a queenside majority with
b2-b4-b5, but this idea has to be handled with care. Insufficient preparing
may run into Black's effective piece counterplay.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6
4. e3 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O {The Schlechter Slav is classified by
the ECO under a Gruenfeld code and not without reasons, as this line combines
the ideas of both openings. The game will soon become relevant for the
examined structure.} Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e6 10. Rd1 Nbd7 {[#]} 11. b4 $6 {
Slightly premature.} (11. b3 {and}) (11. Qe2 {are more consistent.}) 11... dxc4
12. Bxc4 {Our thematic central structure has arisen a bit later through
transposition, but the essence of the general discourse remains the same.} Nb6
13. Bb3 Nbd5 ({It is hard to say why Smyslov refrained from} 13... Nfd5 {
Maybe he feared that after} 14. e4 ({If} 14. Nxd5 cxd5 {the knight would
already be close to the c4-square.}) 14... Nxb4 15. a3 Na6 {his kingside
defense would be weakened, but there is no obvious way for White to take
advantage of this.}) 14. Na4 {To justify his previous play White needs
sacrificing a pawn.} ({If} 14. Nxd5 cxd5 $11 {/=/+ the knight will sooner or
later land on d6-c4, taking advantage of White's premature activity.}) 14...
Nxb4 15. e4 Nd7 16. Ba3 a5 17. Rac1 Qh4 18. Nb2 Rfd8 19. Nc4 Bf8 $15 {Black
has regrouped perfectly and White has not much to show for the sacrificed pawn.
} 0-1

