{The plan based on ...c7-c5 (or ...c6-c5) leads to interesting play only if
White manages to react with d4-d5 (meaning that Black does not have better
control of that square). Otherwise, in most of the cases, the position would
be dully equal after the exchange of the c5- and d4-pawns. Black's counterplay
is slightly different than in the positions with a massive white center as we
will see.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Be2 dxc4 7.
Bxc4 c5 8. d5 {[#]} Ne8 $5 ({Since White's e-pawn is not threatening yet,
Black has the time of transferring the knight to d6, thus preparing his
counterplay which can embrace several forms. A classical game went} 8... e6 $6
{this is too straightforward to equalize completely.} 9. dxe6 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1
Bxe6 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Ke2 Nc6 13. Rd1 Rad8 14. Rxd8 Rxd8 15. Ng5 $14 {with
lasting advantage due to the control over the e4-square, Petrosian-Botvinnik,
Moscow 1963. In this fragment, we see the benefits of having the pawn on e3
rather than on e4. In the latter case, there would be no blockade on e4 and
Black would have the d4-square for the knight.}) 9. O-O Nd6 10. Be2 Bg4 11. Nd2
({If} 11. e4 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 (12. gxf3 f5 {is also good for Black}) 12... b5 {
followed by ..Nd7 Black has stability on dark squares and queenside
counterplay.}) 11... Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Qb6 {[#]} 13. Nc4 {Exchanging the perfectly
placed black knight.} ({If} 13. e4 {Black can weaken White's light squares
even more with} Qa6 14. Qxa6 Nxa6 15. a3 {Preventing ...Nb4.} Rfe8 $5 $15 {
Planning ...e7-e6, which would be quite molesting for White due to his delayed
development.} 16. f4 $6 Bd4+ 17. Kh1 f6 {followed by ...e7-e6 anyway.}) 13...
Nxc4 (13... Qa6 14. Nxd6 Qxe2 15. Nxe2 exd6 $15 {may be even better, rwaching
a perfect Benoni.}) 14. Qxc4 Qb4 15. Qd3 (15. Qxb4 cxb4 16. Ne2 Rc8 {leaves
White terribly underdeveloped.}) 15... Nd7 16. e4 c4 17. Qc2 Nc5 $15 {followed
by ...Nd3 soon with obvious black advantage.} 1/2-1/2

