{Black's most usual plan remains preparing ...e7-e5. There are two basic ways
of doing this, with ...Nbd7 or ...Nc6. The former looks more flexible, but
puts less pressure on White, as in the following typical game:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. Rc1 O-O 6. e3 c6 7. Nf3 Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qa5
10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. O-O dxc4 12. Bxc4 e5 13. Bh2 exd4 14. exd4 {Since there is no
pressure on d4 and Black does not control the d5-square that well yet, the
Isolani is more of a strength than a weakness. Black needs being careful given
the potential threat d4-d5, turning the bishops into an irresistible power.}
Qb4 ({Black decides to start queenside counterplay and forcing the
light-squared bishop releasing the pressure on d5.} 14... Nb6 15. Bb3 Rad8 16.
Be5 Nfd5 17. Ne4 {fails neutralizing White's pressure as the b3-bishop is very
stable.}) 15. Bb3 Nb6 16. Rfd1 a5 {[#]} 17. Rb1 $6 {After this passive move
Black gets comfortable play. White should choose a way of breaking the centre.}
({True,} 17. d5 Nfxd5 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Bxd5 cxd5 20. Qxd5 {doesn't seem to
offer more than a symblic initiative.}) ({But} 17. Be5 {is more consistent.}
Nfd7 (17... a4 {runs into} 18. Nxa4 Nxa4 19. Rc4 Qb5 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Qxf6
Nxb2 22. Rc5 $16 {with strong initiative.}) 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. d5 a4 20. dxc6
Ne5 (20... bxc6 21. Nxa4 {wins a pawn.}) 21. Qe2 Nxc6 22. Bd5 Rae8 23. Qf3 {
and Black has to struggle a bit still.}) 17... a4 18. Bc2 Rfe8 19. a3 Qe7 20.
g4 h6 {with at least equal play due to the stability on d5.} 1/2-1/2

