{More typically, Black prepares the central break with ...Nc6. This plan puts
immediate pressure on d4, forcing White releasing the tension. ***Exchanging
on e5 usually frees Black's play, as in the following game:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6
3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Qa4+ Bd7 7. Qb3 Nb6 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 a5
10. a4 Nc6 11. O-O e5 {[#]} 12. Nxe5 ({In principle the critical reaction to
the central break is} 12. d5 {but White probably feared that his delayed
development would offer Black the initiative. This is only partly true, but
the game move is even less favorable.} e4 $5 ({More ambitious than} 12... Nb4
13. e4 c6 14. Bg5 {with normal play for this plan.}) 13. Nxe4 (13. dxc6 exf3
14. Bxf3 bxc6 {offers Black proper compensation for the shattered structure
because of the better development and the queenside pressure.}) 13... Nb4 14.
Nc5 (14. Nc3 c6 15. dxc6 Be6 16. Qd1 bxc6 {offers Black considerable advance
in development compensating for the pawn.}) 14... Qe7 15. Nxd7 Nxd7 $11 {
To all probability Black will soon retrieve the pawn with ...Nb6.}) 12... Nxe5
13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. e4 {In order to develop the bishop White needs weakening the
d4-square which will have long term effects.} Be6 15. Qc2 c6 {Black has
excellent development while White is still struggling to complete it as the
bishop does not have stable squares.} 16. Be3 ({Of course} 16. Bh6 $2 {loses to
} Qh4) 16... Nc4 17. Bc5 Re8 18. Rfd1 Qc7 (18... Qf6 $17 {followed by ...b7-b6,
preventing the exchange of the problem bishop may have been even better.}) 19.
g3 b6 20. Bd4 Rad8 $1 {Keeping the control over the d4-square.} 21. Bxe5 Qxe5
22. h4 h5 23. Bxc4 Bxc4 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Rd1 Rd4 $1 $15 {with obvious black
initiative.} 0-1

