{But the structure from the previous game does not always favor Black. It
greatly depends on the piece placement. If White has superior development then
the attack with the e and f pawns could be harming.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3
Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nc3 Nb6 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. e3 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. b3 e5
11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Bb2 c6 14. Qc2 {[#]White is already slightly
better developed, but the next move is a surprising mistake from an all life
Gruenfeld specialist.} Bf5 $6 {Obviously, Black wanted to weaken the d4-square,
but he will never manage to occupy it. The last move just offers a tempo for
free.} 15. e4 Be6 16. Rad1 Qe7 17. f4 Bg7 18. f5 {The e6-bishop does not have
good squares already.} Qc5+ {Paradoxically, the queen exchange will not
diminish Wite's pressure.} 19. Qf2 Qxf2+ 20. Rxf2 {This way, the rooks are
ready to get doubled along the d- or f-file, according to the necessities.} Bd7
21. Na4 $5 {A fine move exchanging two of Black's key defensive pieces.} Nxa4 (
21... Bxb2 22. Nxb6 axb6 23. Rxb2 {does not make much of a difference.}) 22.
Bxg7 Kxg7 23. bxa4 Bc8 ({Sad necessity as} 23... Rad8 $2 24. Rfd2) ({and} 23...
Re7 $2 24. f6+ {lose material.}) 24. h3 gxf5 25. exf5 f6 26. g4 {With obvious
white advantage and one sided-play in the endgame. Black has no real prospects
of completing his development again.} h6 27. Rfd2 a5 28. Rd8 Kf7 29. R1d6 Rxd8
30. Rxd8 Rb8 31. Kf2 Ke7 32. Rh8 h5 33. Ke3 hxg4 34. hxg4 Kd6 35. g5 fxg5 36.
f6 Ke6 37. Bh3+ Kxf6 38. Rxc8 Rxc8 39. Bxc8 b5 40. Bd7 bxa4 41. Bxc6 a3 42. Kf3
Ke5 43. Kg4 Kd4 44. Ba4 Kc3 45. Bb3 Kb2 46. Kxg5 a4 47. Bg8 Kc3 48. Kf5 Kd4 49.
Ke6 Kc3 50. Kd5 1-0

