{White's main chances for an advantage are connected with d4-d5. True, this
offers Black a good blockade on d6, but White's space advantage should not be
underestimated.} 1. Nf3 g6 2. c4 Nf6 3. d4 Bg7 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 O-O
7. O-O Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3 e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. e4 {[#]} Bg4 ({This is not only
strategically favorable as the exchange on f3 would increase Black's control
over the dark squares, but also concretely necessary to prepare ... c7-c6, as} 
11... c6 12. d6 {wins the knight..}) 12. a4 {White tries using the time needed
by Black to carry out his plan (...c7-c6 followed by the knight transfer to d6)
to open a new front.} c6 13. a5 Nc4 14. a6 bxa6 15. Qb3 cxd5 16. exd5 Nd6 ({
When having this position with black one year earlier Smejkal in vain
refrained from this natural move in favor of} 16... Nb6 {Portisch-Smejkal,
Reggio Emilia 1985.}) 17. Rxa6 Bc8 $1 {Unblocking the a-pawn.} 18. Ra2 a5 ({
And now} 18... Nef5 19. Re1 Re8 $15 {was the simplest. With such great control
on d4, and d6 Black has a wonderful play.}) 19. Re1 {[#] How would you react
to the pressure on e5?} f6 $2 {Nothing justifies such an ugly move in a good
position. Black in vain weakens the e6-square and his control over d4.} ({
The pawn sacrifice} 19... Nef5 {would offer excellent Black compensation for
instance:} 20. Nxe5 Re8 21. Nf3 Rxe1+ 22. Nxe1 Ba6 {with very active minor
piece play.}) 20. Be3 Ba6 21. Nd2 Nef5 22. Bc5 {Planning Nce4 with lasting
pressure.} Rf7 23. Rea1 Bh6 24. Nce4 Bxd2 25. Nxd2 Rb7 26. Qd1 Bb5 27. b4 a4
28. Nb1 Nd4 29. Nc3 Nb3 30. Rb1 Rc8 31. Nxb5 Rxb5 32. Bxd6 Qxd6 33. Rxa4 Nd4
34. h4 Rcb8 35. Qd2 Rxd5 36. Qa2 Rbb5 37. Ra5 e4 38. Bxe4 1-0

