{[#] What is the easiest way to the equality?} 12... Nd7 {Subjectively,
Black's decision of delaying concrete action with lower rated player, is
understandable and it eventually paid off.} ({But objectively} 12... c5 $1 {
would have equalized at once since d4-d5 is not possible due to the knight's
pin.}) 13. O-O h6 14. Bf4 g5 15. Bg3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 O-O (16... Bf5 17. Bd3 (17.
e4 Bg6) (17. Ne4 Nf6 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Bd3 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 e6 {[%cal Gh6h5]})
17... Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Rd8) {[#]White played} 17. a3 {obviously planning to take
over the control over the whole board with b2-b4.} Bf5 $1 {Indeed, a necessary
preparing move before breaking the center. With hindsight, White could have
punished Black's previous hesitation with 17.Bd3+/=.} ({If} 17... c5 $2 18. d5
$1 Bg4 {White wins a pawn with} 19. Nxg5 $1 hxg5 20. Bxg4 $16) 18. Bd3 (18. e4
Bg6 {with perfect bishops coordination and followed by ...e7-e5}) ({or} 18. Qc1
e5 {offer Black good counterplay.}) 18... Bxd3 19. Qxd3 c5 $11 (19... e5 {
is less recommmendable now due to} 20. Qf5 $14) 20. b4 $5 {It is White's trun
to be ambitious.} (20. Nd5) (20. d5 Rad8 21. e4 a6) 20... cxb4 21. axb4 Qxb4
22. Rfb1 Qd6 23. Qe4 ({Only not} 23. Rxb7 $2 Nc5 $17) 23... Nf6 24. Qxb7 Rfb8
$15 {and Black gradually took over the initiative.} 0-1

