1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5 {Since Black's central pawn does not enjoy
the support of any colleague, this is a logical move, increasing the pressure
on d5. It must have been not by chance that when confronted with the new
opening invented by Ernst Gruenfeld Alekhine reacted precisely this way. And
it is also remarkable that he did not understand the finesses of the opening,
as he eventually lost.} Ne4 {The standard reaction. Instead of looking for a
way to consolidate d5, Black counterattacks.} 5. Bh4 {The most popular answer,
but in practice several alternatives have been tried.} (5. h4 {is extravagant
but not very effective as the threat h4-h5 is not real yet.} Bg7 6. e3 (6. Nxd5
c6 7. Nc3 Nxg5 8. hxg5 Qxd4 {favours Black.}) 6... c5 7. cxd5 Nxc3 8. bxc3 Qxd5
9. Qf3 Qxf3 10. Nxf3 Bf5 ({This rare move prevents Rb1 and is better than} 
10... Nc6 11. Rb1 {causing Black some problems with developing the queenside.})
11. Bc4 (11. Bb5+ Nd7 12. Ne5 cxd4 13. cxd4 Bxe5 14. dxe5 a6 15. Bxd7+ Kxd7 {
with at least equal play.}) 11... Nc6 12. O-O (12. h5 h6 13. Bf4 g5 $15) 12...
h6 ({I prefer this slightly over} 12... Rc8 13. Rac1 Na5 14. Be2 Be6 15. e4 Bc4
{½-½ Tomashevsky, E (2696)-Salgado Lopez, I (2627) Minsk 2017}) 13. Bf4 O-O {
Now that the e7-pawn is not hanging anymore Black can safely castle.} 14. Rac1
Rfd8 15. Rfe1 Bg4 $5 $11 {There is no obvious way for White to put his center
into motion and Black can prepare increasing his pressure with ...Rac8,
possibly ...Bxf3 followed by ...e7-e5.}) (5. Nxe4 dxe4 {is long known to be
comfortable for Black. here is just a sample line.} 6. e3 c5 7. Ne2 Bg7 8. Qd2
Nc6 9. d5 Ne5 10. Nc3 f5 11. Be2 Nf7 12. Bh4 O-O 13. f3 {The only attempt to
fight against Black's perfect stability.} exf3 14. gxf3 {Morozevich,A (2694)
-Carlsen,M (2821) Biel 2011 (½-½, 52)} Nd6 15. O-O a6 16. a4 f4 {with great
play on dark squares.}) (5. cxd5 {is interesting but ineffective} Nxg5 6. h4
Ne4 7. Nxe4 Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qa5 9. h5 Bg7 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Rxh8+ Bxh8 12. Nf3 c5
$15 {Polak,T (2520)-Erdos,V (2640) Austria 2012 (0-1, 31)}) (5. Bf4 {is the
main principled alternative to the main move.} c6 {More about this move in the
main line.} 6. e3 Bg7 7. Nf3 {transposes to Line 2 below.} (7. cxd5 Nxc3 8.
bxc3 cxd5 {leads to a structure which does not face Black with any special
problems. He can prepare to invade c4 or breaking with ...e7-e5. If c3-c4 his
pieces would get space for activating.} 9. Bd3 (9. Bxb8 {is too optimistic:}
Rxb8 10. Qa4+ Bd7 11. Qxa7 Qc7 12. Qa3 O-O 13. Bd3 e5 14. Ne2 e4 15. Bc2 Bb5
$17 {Vanek,T (2251)-Krsek,T (2132) Teplice 2007 (0-1, 50)}) (9. c4 Nc6 10. cxd5
Qxd5 11. Nf3 O-O 12. Be2 Qa5+ 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 Rd8 15. Rhc1 Bf5 16. Ke1
Rac8 $132) 9... O-O 10. Ne2 (10. Nf3 {transposes to Line 2 below.}) 10... Nc6
11. O-O e5) (7. Bd3 Nxc3 8. bxc3 {Jussupow,A (2655)-Timman,J (2620) Linares
1992 (½-½, 55)} e5 $5 9. Bxe5 Bxe5 10. dxe5 Be6 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. Nf3 Nd7 13.
Be2 Qxd1+ 14. Bxd1 Bd5 {Black will retrieve the pawn soon retaining an
excellent square for the knight on c5.})) 5... c6 {Over the decades the main
line involved an early exchange on c3. As this tends to leave White with a
solid center, more recently Black has connected his hopes with pawn grabbing
on c4. But I have long been tempted by the apparently modest last move, after
seeing some old games by Kortschnoj. When I discovered that Eljanov and
Vachier Lagrave have repeatedly played it in recent games, I did not hesitate
to make it our repertoire move. Black's main idea is delaying the moment of a
critical decision in the center. In many lines ...Qa5 is an issue, and a well
timed ...dxc4 may offer him counterplay or even the initiative.} 6. e3 (6. Nf3
{transposes to Line 3 below.}) 6... Qa5 7. Qb3 (7. cxd5 Nxc3 8. Qd2 e6 $5 (8...
cxd5 {Ipatov,A (2454)-Lorenzo de la Riva,L (2331) Badalona 2009 (1-0, 45)} 9.
Ne2 $1 $14) (8... b6 9. bxc3 cxd5 10. c4 $5) 9. bxc3 ({The point is that} 9.
dxe6 $2 {allows Black keeping the extra piece with} Bb4 10. a3 Nd5) 9... cxd5
10. Rb1 (10. Bf6 Rg8 {is not dangerous. Black will soon drive the enemy bishop
away with ...Nd7, when he could even start a kingside pawn attack with ...
g6-g5.}) 10... b6 11. Bb5+ (11. c4 dxc4 12. Qxa5 bxa5 {As we will see, the
double pawns are strong, offering support to the minor pieces.} 13. Bxc4 Bb4+
14. Ke2 Nd7 15. Nf3 O-O 16. Rhc1 Nb6 17. Bd3 Nd5 18. Kf1 Bb7 $132 {/\...Rfc8, .
..Nc3, ><Pa2}) 11... Bd7 12. Bd3 Bc6 13. Ne2 Nd7 14. O-O b5 15. f3 Bh6 $11 {
The position is rather static and Black does not have problems.}) 7... e5 $1 {
A typical pawn sacrifice taking advantage of the fact that White has delayed
the king's knight development.} 8. Bd3 (8. dxe5 g5 9. Bg3 Be6 10. cxd5 Bxd5 11.
Qc2 Nd7 12. Nge2 O-O-O 13. O-O-O (13. f3 Nxg3 14. hxg3 Bb3 $3 15. Qxb3 Nc5 $19
{wins material.}) 13... Nxg3 14. hxg3 (14. Nxg3 Be6 15. f4 gxf4 16. exf4 Bh6 {
retrieves the e5 pawn with obvious advantage.}) 14... Bxa2 $13) 8... exd4 9.
exd4 {Palachev,P (2373)-Timofeev,A (2539) St Petersburg 2015 (0-1, 49)} Bb4 $1
10. Bxe4 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 dxe4 12. Ne2 O-O $13 {The black queen's activity
prevents White creating dangerous threats using his bishop. Besides, Black has
some space advantage, and the c4-square is weak.} *

