1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 {This is the second possible
way of developing the bishop to g5.} Ne4 6. Bf4 ({Due to space limitation, I
will mention the old line} 6. cxd5 Nxg5 7. Nxg5 {only briefly. Black's pair of
bishops offers him comfortable play.} e6 8. Qd2 (8. Nf3 exd5 {leads to a
suitable version of the Carlsbad structure:} 9. e3 O-O 10. Be2 c6 11. O-O Nd7
12. b4 Nb6 13. Qb3 Be6 {Due to the weak c4-square and the bishops' pressure,
White cannot organize b4-b5 easily as Black has ...c6-c5.} 14. Nd2 Qe7 $5 {
An almost unexplored move but a logical one.} 15. a4 Nc8 $5 {followed by ...
Nd6.}) (8. Qa4+ c6 9. dxc6 Nxc6 10. Nf3 Bd7 11. Qd1 Qb6 {offers Black too much
play for the pawn.}) 8... h6 9. Nh3 ({Forcing matters with} 9. Nf3 exd5 10.
Qe3+ {only misplaces the queen:} Be6 11. g3 O-O 12. Bg2 c5 $1 13. Qd2 Nc6 14.
dxc5 d4 15. Na4 Bc4 16. O-O Bb5 $15 {Beliavsky,A (2646)-Sutovsky,E (2655)
Heraklion 2007 (½-½, 52)}) 9... exd5 10. Nf4 O-O 11. e3 Re8 12. Be2 (12.
Nfxd5 c6 13. Nf4 Qxd4 $15) 12... c6 13. O-O Bf8 {Starting taking measures
against the minority's attack.} 14. Nd3 Bf5 15. Rac1 Nd7 16. Na4 Nf6 17. Nac5
Qc7 $15 {Delemarre,J (2471)-Krasenkow,M (2635) Vlissingen 2006 (0-1, 38) Black
is well prepared for starting his kingside counterplay with ...Bd6, ...Re7, ...
Rae8, ...Ne4.}) 6... c6 {The same idea as explained in Line 1.} 7. e3 ({
Clearing matters does not offer chances for an advanatge:} 7. cxd5 Nxc3 8. bxc3
cxd5 9. e3 (9. Bxb8 {is once again premature:} Rxb8 10. Qa4+ Bd7 11. Qxa7 Qc7
12. Qa3 O-O 13. e3 Rfc8 14. Rc1 {Kolas,T-Brameld,A Breda 1994 (0-1, 53)} b5 $15
) 9... Nc6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O (11. h4 Bg4 12. Qc2 Qd7 13. Rc1 Rac8 14. Qb2 {
Thorfinnsson,B (2314)-Gretarsson,H (2505) Seltjarnarnes 2002 (0-1, 53)} f6 15.
Bg3 e5 $15) 11... Be6 12. Ng5 Bf5 13. Rc1 Rc8 14. c4 dxc4 15. e4 Bd7 $1 16. d5
Na5 $15 {White does not seem to have enough compensation, for instance:} 17. e5
b5 18. Ne4 Nb7) 7... O-O 8. Qb3 (8. Bd3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 {Nestorovic,D (2426)
-Atalik, S (2595) Belgrade 2012 (½-½, 38)} dxc4 $5 {Since White's center is
not threatening, Black prepares his counterplay at his leisure.} 10. Bxc4 Nd7
11. Bg3 (11. O-O Nb6 12. Bb3 Nd5 {attacks f4 and c3.}) 11... b5 12. Bd3 (12.
Bb3 {allows} a5 13. a3 c5 {with excellent play.}) 12... Nb6 13. Be4 {Trying to
cross Black's intentions.} Bd7 14. Ne5 Rc8 15. O-O Na4 16. Qd2 Be6 $11 17. Nxc6
$6 Qd7 18. Ne5 Bxe5 19. Bxe5 Nxc3 20. Bf3 f6 21. Bg3 b4 $15 {With overwhelming
queenside activity while White has no obvious chances for a kingside attack.})
8... Qa5 {The thematical pinning move.} 9. cxd5 (9. Bd3 {Should be met with}
Bf5 $1 (9... Na6 {Eljanov,P (2742)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2703) Moscow 2010 (0-1,
29)} 10. cxd5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 cxd5 12. O-O $16) 10. Bxe4 dxe4 11. Nd2 Nd7 12.
Qxb7 e5 13. Nb3 (13. dxe5 Rab8 14. Qxc6 Rxb2 $19) 13... Qd8 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15.
Bxe5 (15. O-O Nxc4 16. Bc7 Qc8 17. Qxc6 Ne5 18. Qd6 Nc4 $11 19. Qc5 Nxb2 $15)
15... Bxe5 16. Qxc6 Qd3 17. Qd5 Bxc3+ 18. bxc3 Qxc3+ 19. Qd2 Qxc4 $11) 9...
Nxc3 10. bxc3 (10. Qxc3 {is like always an important alternative.} Qxc3+ 11.
bxc3 cxd5 12. c4 ({This looks more consistent than} 12. h4 Bf5 13. h5 Rc8 14.
Kd2 Nd7 15. hxg6 hxg6 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 f6 18. Bg3 e5 19. Bb5 exd4 20. exd4
Bf8 $11 {Sakharov,Y-Kortschnoj,V Moscow 1966 (½-½, 30)}) 12... Nc6 13. cxd5
Nb4 14. Kd2 Nxd5 15. Be5 f6 16. Bg3 Rd8 17. Bc4 e6 18. Rhc1 Bf8 19. Rab1 b6
$132) 10... cxd5 11. Be2 b6 {A logical move, aiming at exchanging the bishops,
but no the only playable one.} (11... Nc6 12. O-O Qd8 13. Rfc1 Na5 14. Qb4 b6
15. Nd2 {Taimanov,M-Zaitsev,A Moscow 1969 (1-0, 39)} Re8 16. c4 (16. Bb5 Bd7
17. a4 e5 $11) (16. Nb3 e5 17. dxe5 Nc6 $11) 16... Ba6 $132) 12. O-O Ba6 13.
Bxa6 Nxa6 14. Rfc1 (14. Rac1 Rac8 15. c4 dxc4 16. Rxc4 {Habu,Y (2400)-Vachier
Lagrave,M (2715) Tokyo 2012 (0-1, 41)} Rxc4 17. Qxc4 b5 $11 {Due to the
hanging a2 pawn cmbined with the threat ...Nb4 White has not enough freedom
for his queen.}) 14... Rac8 15. c4 {Krasenkow,M (2632)-Cichocki,A (2332)
Dzwirzyno 2004 (1-0, 47)} dxc4 (15... Nc5 16. dxc5 dxc4 17. Qxc4 Bxa1 18. Rxa1
Qxc5 19. Qf1 Qc4 $13) 16. Rxc4 Rxc4 17. Qxc4 b5 18. Qc6 (18. Qb3 Rc8 $13) 18...
Nb4 19. Qb7 Nd3 20. Qxe7 Qc3 21. Rf1 Nxf4 22. exf4 Bxd4 23. Qd7 Bb6 24. Qxb5
Rc8 $44 *

