1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. Bg5 Ne4 6. Bh4 c6 7. e3 Qa5 8. Qb3 (
8. cxd5 {leads to familiar play:} Nxc3 9. Qd2 (9. bxc3 Qxc3+ 10. Nd2 {offers
just adequate compensation for the pawn, without overstepping the bearable
limits:} Bg4 11. Qc1 Qxc1+ 12. Rxc1 cxd5 13. Bb5+ Kd8 14. O-O a6 15. Ba4 Nd7
16. Bb3 Be6 $11) 9... cxd5 10. bxc3 (10. Qxc3 {is less interesting.} Nc6 11.
Qxa5 Nxa5 $11 12. b4 $6 {Schleifer,M (2240)-Bailey,D (2355) Toronto 1992 (0-1,
59)} Nc4 $1) 10... Nc6 11. Rb1 (11. c4 Qxd2+ 12. Nxd2 Be6 13. Rb1 O-O $132)
11... O-O 12. Be2 a6 13. O-O e5 $132 {The c3-pawn will be at least as weak as
the d5-pawn.}) (8. Rc1 $5 {is an interesting pawn sacrifice Which Black should
accept.} Nxc3 ({Instead,} 8... dxc4 $2 {as I played against my dear person, is
bad:} 9. Bxc4 g5 10. Bg3 Nxg3 11. fxg3 $1 $16 {With annoying kingside pressure,
Yugina-Marin St. Petersburg rapid 2017}) 9. Rxc3 (9. bxc3 Qxa2 10. c5 Qa5 11.
Bd3 Nd7 $13 {White's space advantage compensates for the missing pawn, but
Black is quite solid.}) 9... Qxa2 10. cxd5 Qxd5 11. Bc4 Qd8 $13 {Once again,
White's compensation is obvious, but Black should not be too worried.}) 8...
dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nd6 $1 {A perfect square for the knight. With the bishop on f4
this move would not be possible.} 10. Be2 ({Giving up the light-squared bishop
frees Black's play.} 10. O-O Nxc4 11. Qxc4 Be6 12. Qe2 (12. Qd3 Na6 13. a3 Rd8
14. b4 Qh5 15. Ne2 Bf5 16. Qb3 Bg4 17. Nf4 Qf5 $11 18. Qd3 $2 Qxd3 19. Nxd3
Bxf3 20. gxf3 Bxd4 $1 $17 {Enklaar,B-Kortschnoj,V (2670) Amsterdam 1972 (0-1,
46)}) 12... h6 13. e4 g5 14. Bg3 Bg4 15. h3 Bh5 16. Qe3 Nd7 17. Nd2 c5 18. d5
Qb4 $13 {Moiseenko,A (2559)-Eljanov,P (2540) Kharkov 2002 (½-½, 27)}) 10...
Be6 11. Qc2 Nf5 {After driving back one bishop, the knight goes hundting the
other one.} 12. Bg5 (12. Bg3 {offers Black too easy play.} Nxg3 13. hxg3 O-O
14. O-O (14. b4 Qxb4 15. Rb1 Qa5 16. Rxb7 c5 $11) 14... c5 15. d5 (15. Rfd1 Nc6
16. d5 Bf5 17. e4 Nd4 $132) 15... Bg4 $132) 12... Nd7 {Slightly over-ambitious.
} ({The simplest is} 12... c5 13. dxc5 Qxc5 $11) 13. O-O h6 14. Bf4 g5 15. Bg3
Nxg3 16. hxg3 (16. fxg3 Nf6) 16... O-O (16... Bf5 $1 17. Bd3 (17. e4 Bg6) (17.
Ne4 Nf6 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. Bd3 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 e6 {[%cal Gh6h5]}) 17... Bxd3 18.
Qxd3 Rd8 $11) 17. a3 (17. Bd3 $1 $14) 17... Bf5 18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 c5 $11
20. b4 $5 {It is White's turn to avoid simple equality.} cxb4 21. axb4 Qxb4 22.
Rfb1 (22. Ne4 Qb6) 22... Qd6 23. Qe4 (23. Nb5 Qb8 24. Qa3 Bf6 25. Nc3 e6 26.
Ne4 Bd8 $13) 23... Nf6 24. Qxb7 Rfb8 $15 {Raetsky,A (2399)-Eljanov,P (2613)
Biel 2004 (0-1, 37)} *

