1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 {This move puts much less immediate
pressure on Black than Bg5. True, in some cases White can consider exchanging
everything on d5 and grabbing the c7-pawn, but this is supposed to offer Black
good compensation. The main point is different. After Black breaks the center
with the thematical ...c7-c5, the bishop will exert pressure along an
important diagonal in a position with an open center. White mainly plays for
an advance in development and initiative and not for space advantage or mobile
center. As we will soon find out, for our repertoire it doesn't matter if
White inserts Nf3 before developing the bishop.} Bg7 5. e3 c6 $5 {This has
been my own main choice at two different moments of my career when I had the
Grunfeld as my main opening. Its positive points are avoiding the mass of
forced variations (with at most draw at stake if White knows what he is doing)
after ...c7-c5 or the c7-pawn grabbing after 5...0-0. In principle, this looks
like an improved version for White of both the Schlechter Variation and the
Fianchetto Exchange Slav. White's bishop is more active than in the former,
and he can choose a better moment for exchanging on d5 (for instance, after ...
Nbd7). This is the first thought coming up to mind, but things are less
one-sided. The point is that the bishop is also exposed on f4, making ...Nxd5
the best way of meeting the central exchange. In some lines, Black can play ...
dxc4 followed by ...Nd5, with similar evaluation.} 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Qb3 {This is
one of the classical main lines. White intends inhibiting the c8-bishop's
development.} (7. cxd5 $6 Nxd5 8. Bg3 {This transposes to the recommended line
after 7.Be2 with a whole extra tempo for Black, as White's bishop is on f1 and
not c4.} ({If} 8. Nxd5 {Black has a choice.} cxd5 (8... Qxd5 {in the spirit of
the Grunfeld is also possible but has not been played between strong players.
In fact, 7.cxd5 is not popular and rightly so.}) 9. Bd3 {This transposes to a
sub-line from Farago-Kortschnoj below, line 7.Be2. Black has no problems at
all.}) ({The same comment as after 8.Bg3 applies to} 8. Be5 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Qa5 (
9... Bg4 {similar to an analysis from line 7.dxc4 is also possible.}) (9... c5
10. Bxg7 Kxg7 {½-½ Kovacs, L-Timoshenko,G (2530) Decin 1978 is not very
relevant, but equal.}) 10. Qd2 Nd7 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Be2 e5 $11 {Black has
made full use of ...c7-c6 and not turned it into a loss of time by playing ...
c6-c5. Padevsky,N (2430)-Filip,M (2510) Moscow 1956 (½-½, 25)}) 8... c5 {
Without a bishop on c4, this equalizes at once.} 9. Bc4 (9. Qb3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 {
Bulava,P (2095)-Klimes,J Ostrava 2006 (½-½, 29)} cxd4 11. exd4 Be6 12. Qxb7
Qa5 13. Qb2 Rc8 14. Rc1 Bh6 15. Nd2 Nd7 $36) (9. Rc1 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxc3 11.
Rxc3 Nc6 $17 {Piroli,M-Mueller,M Osnabrueck 1994 (½-½, 64)}) 9... Nb6 10. Bb3
cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 {A typical Grunfeld structure. The c-pawn is
not weak, and it actually helps to start queenside counterplay. Kotronias,V 
(2565)-Dimitrov,A (2321) Hydra 2015 (1-0, 48)}) (7. Be2 {This (and 7.Bd3,
which can be met in the same way) implies wasting a tempo after} dxc4 8. Bxc4 {
which is useful for Black since it clears the d5-square for his knight.} Nd5 9.
Bg3 (9. Bxd5 cxd5 10. Qb3 e6 11. O-O Nc6 12. Rfc1 {White seems to be more
active in this symmetrical position, but Black has two bishops and a coherent
regrouping plan.} f6 {The most consistent regrouping plan, typical for
Kortschnoj.} 13. Qa3 Rf7 14. Nb5 a6 15. Nd6 Rd7 16. Nxc8 Rxc8 17. h3 e5 18. Bg3
e4 19. Nd2 f5 $11 {Farago,I (2475)-Kortschnoj,V (2630) Rotterdam 1987 EXT 1997
(½-½, 56)}) (9. Be5 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bg4 $5 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Qb3 (12. h3 Bxf3
13. Qxf3 Nd7 14. O-O e5 $11) 12... b5 (12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 b5 14. Be2 Nd7 15.
f4 Nb6 16. Bf3 Rc8 17. h4 $5 $14) 13. Be2 Nd7 14. O-O Nb6 15. h3 {Kraidman, Y 
(2440)-Roos,D (2360) Manchester 1981 (0-1, 52)} Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Qd6 {The knight
is not weaker than the bishop. There are many blockading ideas due to the big
pawn number.} 17. Rfd1 a6 18. Rac1 Rfc8 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gc6c5]} 19. e4 e5 $11)
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qa5 {This causes White some problems as all the ways of
defending c3 implies some commitment.} 11. Rc1 (11. Qd2 {slightly exposes the
queen.} Bf5 12. O-O Nd7 13. Bb3 Rad8 14. Rfe1 Nc5 15. Bc2 Ne4 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17.
Qb2 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Rd7 19. a3 Qh5 20. Qe2 e5 $17 {Mueller,S (1763) -Rahn,M 
(1562) Schney 2013 (½-½, 45)}) (11. Qb3 {Oster,K (1760)-Lindner,M (1961)
Stetten 2005 (0-1, 61) It is best to start playing against the exposed white
pieces at once:} b5 $1 12. Bd3 Be6 13. Qb2 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6]} 14. a4 $2 Nc5 $1
15. Bc2 Nxa4 16. Bxa4 bxa4 17. O-O c5 $15) {Rashkovsky,N (2511) -Kolbus,D 
(2297) Biel 2002 EXT 2003 (1-0, 47) Once again Black should have played
resolutely:} 11... b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 13. O-O c5 $11 14. c4 (14. a4 a6 15. axb5
axb5 16. dxc5 Na6 $11) (14. Qe2 Nd7 $13) (14. dxc5 Na6 $11) 14... bxc4 15. Bxc4
Nd7 16. d5 Nb6 17. Qb3 Qb4 $13) (7. h3 $5 {This apparently inoffensive move
makes a lot of sense. White prevents ...Bg4 and clears the retreat for the
bishop. The only drawback is that this move does little for the development.}
Ne4 $5 ({h2-h3 is much more useful than Rc1 in the line} 7... Be6 8. Qb3 Qb6 9.
c5 Qxb3 10. axb3 Nbd7 11. b4 a6 $14 {allowing White keeping his bishop and
having the rook on the right file. (compare to line 5)}) (7... c5 $5 8. dxc5
Ne4 9. Rc1 Nd7 10. cxd5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 {leads to a not bery dangerous version
of the Bf4 Gruenfeld with ...c7-c5, where the extra tempo h2-h3 may not be
essential.}) (7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Nd5 {is also playable, almost transposing to
the recommended line in after 7.Be2, but this time the additional h2-h3 may be
useful sometimes.}) 8. Bd3 (8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Nd2 f5 $11) (8. cxd5 Nxc3 9. bxc3
cxd5 10. c4 Nc6 11. Be2 Qa5+ 12. Qd2 {Portisch,F (2370) -Lenart,E (2220)
Harkany 1998 (1-0, 34)} dxc4 13. Bxc4 Bf5 $11) (8. Qb3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 b6 10. Be2
Ba6 11. O-O c5 12. Rfc1 Nc6 13. cxd5 Na5 14. Qd1 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Qxd5 16. Rab1
