1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 {The fianchetto system is an inspired
psychological choice. Indeed, White is developing in the spirit of the
Grunfeld himself, meaning that in this double Grunfeld he will be a tempo up.
But things get this way only if Black is too obstinately playing for equality.
Otherwise, play may become attractive.} d5 5. cxd5 (5. Nf3 {will be examined
in line 8.}) 5... Nxd5 6. e4 {White tries taking advantage of the used move
order. This would not work if he played Nf3 earlier.} ({The old-fashioned} 6.
Nc3 {deserves mentioning.} Nb6 ({In the past} 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 c5 8. e3 {
followed by Ne2 was an important line. But there is no need strengthening
White's center as the main move leads to positions similar to those examined
in the main lines.}) 7. e3 e5 8. d5 (8. dxe5 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Bxe5 10. Bd2 Na6 11.
Rc1 c6 12. Nf3 Bg7 13. Bc3 O-O 14. Ke2 Be6 {0-1 (60) Lundin,J (2294)-Danin,A 
(2538) Prague 2011}) (8. Nf3 Nc6) (8. Nge2 O-O 9. O-O {1/2-1/2 (60) Kortschnoj,
V (2670)-Stean,M (2420) London 1976} exd4 10. Nxd4 Qe7 11. b3 Rd8 12. a4 c5 13.
Ba3 Qe5 14. a5 cxd4 15. axb6 Nc6 $15 {1-0 (28) Lutikov,A-Kotkov,Y Perm 1960})
8... c6 9. e4 cxd5 10. exd5 O-O 11. Nge2 Na6 12. O-O Bf5 13. b3 e4 {1/2-1/2 
(64) Laylo,D (2489)-Salvador,R (2484) Boracay Island 2012}) ({For} 6. Nf3 {
see line 7.}) 6... Nb4 $5 {I had a strong attraction towards this move since I
was a teen-ager and after checking its actuality I decided making it our main
line.} ({The most fashionable continuation is} 6... Nb6 7. Ne2 c5 8. d5 {
but generally the d5-pawn seems to be quite strong, requiring from Black long
term accuracy for neutralizing it.}) 7. d5 (7. a3 {is actually drivint the
knight closer to the important squares:} N4c6 8. d5 Nd4 9. Ne2 ({The most
flexible move order for if} 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Nge2 c5 11. O-O e5 12. dxe6 Bxe6 $15
{Fuster,G-Szabo,L Budapest 1948 (0-1, 26)}) ({or} 9. Be3 c5 $11) 9... Bg4 ({
Without a knight on c3} 9... c5 {is less accurate:} 10. O-O O-O 11. Nxd4 cxd4
12. Nd2 $14) 10. Nbc3 c6 11. O-O cxd5 12. exd5 Bf3 13. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 14. Kg2 Ne5 {
The structure offers both sides chances. Black will try safely blocking on d6,
while also using the weakened kingside.} 15. Be3 O-O 16. Bd4 Nbd7 17. Nf4 a6
18. Nd3 Nc4 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Re1 Rc8 21. Qe2 Re8 $11 {Brynell,S (2485)
-Timofeev,A (2613) Cappelle-la-Grande 2013 (½-½, 44)}) (7. Ne2 {loses a pawn
without much compensation:} Bxd4 $1 8. O-O (8. Nxd4 Qxd4 $1) 8... Bg7) 7... c6
8. a3 ({Now or on the next move White should drive the enemy knight away for if
} 8. Ne2 cxd5 9. exd5 $6 Bf5 10. O-O O-O 11. Nbc3 N8a6 {Black gets too much
activity.}) 8... N4a6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Nge2 cxd5 11. exd5 Nd7 12. O-O Ne5 {
Again the same type of structure, offering plenty of ideas to both sides.} 13.
h3 (13. Bf4 {Euwe,M-Barcza,G Venice 1948 (½-½, 28)} Nc4 14. b3 Nd6) (13. b3
Bg4 {Donner,J-Teschner,R Duesseldorf 1951 (½-½, 62)}) 13... Nc4 14. b3 Nd6 {
Once a knight has landed here things cannot go really wrong for Black.} 15. Bf4
(15. Bb2 Nc5 16. b4 Nce4 17. Na4 Bxb2 18. Nxb2 a5 $132 {Sachdev,T (2423)-Gupta,
A (2521) Differdange 2008 (½-½, 30)}) (15. Be3 Bd7 16. Bd4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Qb6
18. Qxb6 axb6 19. Nd4 Rfc8 20. Rfc1 Nc5 21. Nce2 Bb5 $132 {Dautov,R (2606)
-Hracek,Z (2612) Germany 2001 (0-1, 88)}) 15... Bd7 16. Rc1 Qa5 17. a4 (17. Nb1
Rfc8 18. Bg5 Rxc1 19. Nxc1 Bf5 20. Bxe7 Nc8 21. d6 Nxe7 22. dxe7 Re8 $15 {
Zaichik,G (2510)-Kudrin,S (2575) Philadelphia 1993 (½-½, 27)}) 17... Rfc8 18.
Bd2 Qd8 19. g4 Rc7 20. Ng3 {Ilincic,Z (2542)-Ftacnik,L (2618) Herceg Novi 2001
(1-0, 44)} Nb4 $5 $13 *

