1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nf3 {This is a more
harmonious system of development, but it also puts less immediate pressure on
Black.} Nb6 $1 {For reasons explained below it is best starting the central
counterplay before castling.} 7. Nc3 $1 {Also the most consistent answer.} ({If
} 7. O-O Nc6 8. e3 e5 {White does not have the thematic d4-d5 anymore.} 9. Nc3
(9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bxe5 12. Nc3 c6 13. e4 Bg7 14. f4 O-O 15.
e5 f6 $11) 9... exd4 (9... O-O 10. d5 Ne7 11. e4 Bg4 {approximately transposes
below, but in principle, it is easier to delay castling in this setup, too.})
10. exd4 O-O 11. Bg5 {The only way of bringing some life in a not very
interesting position.} f6 12. Qb3+ (12. Bf4 Be6 $11) 12... Kh8 13. Be3 Na5 14.
Qd1 {Jasnikowski,Z (2451)-Palus,R (2228) Zakopane 2000 (1-0, 49)} Be6 $11) 7...
Nc6 8. e3 ({With the castles inserted,} 8. d5 {would be a decent alternative
but here} Bxc3+ $1 {comes with a check, preventing the intermediary dxc6.} 9.
bxc3 Qxd5 {Black has won a pawn, and the thing that he has not castled on the
weakened wing is also important.} 10. O-O Qxd1 11. Rxd1 f6 12. Nd4 Bd7 $15 {
Tsybulnik,A (2245)-Shomoev,A (2528) Saratov 2006 (0-1, 26)}) ({White has two
ways of ignoring the threat on d4. They both lead to exciting play but tend to
result in a draw:} 8. O-O Nxd4 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Qxd4 (10. Nb5 Qc4 11. Qb3 O-O
12. Qxc4 Nxc4 13. Nxc7 Rb8 14. Nd5 {The position is symmetrical, and the main
thing now is development:} Be6 $1 15. Nxe7+ Kh8 16. Nd5 Nxb2 17. Rb1 {½-½
Kempinski,R (2653)-Hracek,Z (2581) Germany 2005}) (10. a4 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bxc3
12. bxc3 a5 13. Bf4 c6 14. Bc7 {Prevetning ...Nc4.} Nd7 {WHite's compensation
is obvious, but it should reach for a draw only.} 15. Bh3 {Preventing castling.
} Ra7 16. Rab1 b5 {Emms,J (2460)-Howell,D (2698) Coventry 2015 (0-1, 37) Black
has at least equal play.}) 10... Bxd4 11. Nb5 Be5 12. Bf4 (12. f4 $6 a6 13.
fxe5 axb5 14. Be3 Nd7 $15 {Blechzin,I (2438)-Jansa,V (2439) Bayerisch
Eisenstein 2013 (0-1, 52)}) 12... Bxf4 13. gxf4 Kd8 14. Rfd1+ Nd7 15. Rac1 c6 {
This has been played in several games. White's compensation is mainly optical.
The central question is whether Black can free himself to start playing for a
win.}) (8. Bf4 O-O 9. O-O (9. e3 {leaves the bishop in some danger} h6 10. h4
Bg4 11. Rc1 e5 12. dxe5 Nc4 13. Qxd8 Rfxd8 14. O-O N4xe5 $15 {Ju,W (2443)-Negi,
P (2615) St Petersburg 2009 (0-1, 59)}) 9... Nxd4 10. Nxd4 e5 $1 11. Nc6 {
The only way to cause some structural damage.} Qxd1 12. Ne7+ Kh8 13. Rfxd1 exf4
14. Nxc8 Raxc8 15. Bxb7 Rb8 (15... Rce8 $5 $146 {is also worth testing. The
threat is ...Bxc3 followed by ...Rxe2.} 16. Bf3 fxg3 17. hxg3 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Kg7
19. a4 a5 20. Rd4 Re5 $11) 16. Ba6 fxg3 17. hxg3 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Na4 $11 {
This has been tested several times, but just as in the subline above Black's
stability on dark squares ensures him equality.}) 8... e5 9. d5 (9. O-O {
transposes to 7.0-0 above.}) 9... Ne7 10. e4 Bg4 11. O-O c6 {We have used some
examples from this line in the latest article about structures.} 12. h3 (12. a4
O-O 13. a5 Nc4 14. Qb3 (14. a6 bxa6 15. Qb3 cxd5 16. exd5 Nd6 17. Rxa6 Bc8 $1 {
Unblocking the a-pawn.} 18. Ra2 {Smejkal,J (2550)-Doncevic,D (2345) Germany
1986 (1-0, 38)} Nef5 $1 19. Re1 Re8 $15 {With such great control on d4 and d6
Black has a wonderful play.}) 14... cxd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Qxc4 Ne7 17. Be3 Nc6
{White can try fighting for the initiative in an almost symmetrical position,
but Black should be able to keep equality.} 18. Qb5 (18. a6 Qc7 19. Rfc1 Rac8
20. b4 Qd7 21. axb7 Qxb7 22. Bc5 Rfd8 $11 {[%cal Gg7f8]}) 18... Qc7 19. Rfc1
Rfc8 20. h3 Be6 21. Bf1 a6 22. Qa4 h6 $11 {Huebner,R (2585)-Rogoff,K (2480)
Biel 1976 (1-0, 41)}) 12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 {The only ambitious move.} (13. Bxf3
O-O 14. Qb3 cxd5 15. Nxd5 Nbxd5 16. exd5 Nf5 $11 {planning ...Nd6 offers Black
perfect stability as} 17. Qxb7 $2 Nd4 18. Bg2 Qd6 $19 {traps the queen soon
with ...Rfb8.}) 13... cxd5 14. Nxd5 (14. exd5 Nf5 15. d6 Rb8 16. Rd1 O-O 17.
Be3 Nd4 18. Bxd4 exd4 19. Nb5 Nc4 20. Qd5 Nxb2 21. Rxd4 Bxd4 22. Qxd4 Qb6 $13 {
With just some compensation for the exchange, Aronian,L (2724) -Bologan,V 
(2700) Merida 2005 (1-0, 46)}) 14... Nbxd5 15. Rd1 O-O 16. exd5 (16. Bg5 Qd6
$146 17. Rac1 Rac8 18. exd5 Nf5 $11) 16... Nf5 17. d6 {The only way to keep
the position dynamic.} (17. Qb3 Nd6 $11 {is absolutely safe for Black.}) 17...
Nd4 18. Qxb7 (18. Qd5 Rc8 {/\...Rc6.}) 18... Qxd6 19. Be3 Qe6 $5 $146 {
Unpinning the knight but also attacking h3 in order to avoid Qxa8.} 20. Rd2 (
20. Kh2 Nc2 $11) 20... a5 $13 *

