1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 d5 5. Nf3 {White delays the exchange in
the center, reckoning with the fact that this implies activating the enemy
knight, at the same time with exposing it.} dxc4 ({it is best to play this at
once as after} 5... O-O {White could return to the exchange path with} 6. cxd5
Nxd5 7. O-O Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 {when he would have the additional option} 9. d5) 6.
Na3 {This is the most flexible way of retrieving the pawn.} (6. Qa4+ {wastes
too much time with the queen:} Nfd7 7. Qxc4 Nb6 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. e3 ({
Curiously, the seemingly more active} 10. Rd1 {exposes the rook:} Bf5 11. e4
Bg4 12. d5 Bxf3 {No intermediate dxc6 here!} 13. Bxf3 Nd4 14. Qd3 c6 $132)
10... Bf5 11. e4 Bg4 12. d5 Bxf3 13. dxc6 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 bxc6 15. Rd1 (15. Qxc6
Qd6 16. Qc2 Rfd8 17. a4 a5 18. Ra3 Qe6 $132 {Khotenashvili,B (2526)-Wei,Y 
(2675) Caleta 2015 (0-1, 49)}) 15... Qe8 16. a4 f5 17. a5 Nc8 {Havlicek,L 
(2304)-Bagi,M (2309) Slovakia 2012 (½-½, 77)}) ({If} 6. O-O {Black is not
forced to transpose to the main line by castling. Instead he can try} c6 {
when White finds it more difficult retrieving the pawn than in some similar
Slav lines, due to the bishop's pressure along the long diagonal.} 7. a4 {
ensures retrieving the pawn but seriously weakens the queenside.} (7. Ne5 {
weakens the d4-pawn.} Ng4 8. Nxg4 (8. f4 O-O 9. e3 Nxe5 10. fxe5 c5 11. Na3 Nc6
$17 {Nikolic,P (2625)-Anand,V (2715) Munich 1994 (0-1, 40)}) 8... Bxg4 9. Be3
Nd7 10. Na3 Nb6 11. Rc1 Be6 {Renette,H (2320)-Kovchan,A (2554) Gent 2009 
(½-½, 34)}) 7... Ne4 8. Qc2 (8. Na3 Nd6 9. Bf4 O-O 10. Rc1 Na6 11. Nxc4 Nxc4
12. Rxc4 Be6 13. Rc1 Bd5 14. e3 Qa5 $11 {Tkachiev,V (2649)-Khairullin,I (2658)
Khanty-Mansiysk 2013 (½-½, 34) In this line the queenside weakening surely
tells, offering Black comfortable targets.}) 8... Nd6 9. e4 (9. Nbd2 O-O 10.
Nxc4 Bf5 11. Qc3 {Matnadze, A (2428)-Perpinya Rofes, L (2395) Barbera del
Valles 2011 (½-½, 74)} c5 $11) 9... Na6 10. Na3 Be6 11. Qe2 O-O 12. Rd1 Qc8
13. e5 Nf5 14. Nxc4 Rd8 {With reasonable play for Black due to White's
numerous weaknesses, compensating for his space advantage, Horvath, D (2380)
-Erdos, V (2585) Hungary 2016 (0-1, 26)}) 6... c3 {to create counterplay based
on ...c7-c5 Black does best creating a target on c3.} 7. bxc3 O-O 8. O-O c5 9.
e3 {The old classical move.} (9. Ne5 {fails to prevent Black's natural
development:} Nc6 10. Nac4 ({Or if} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Bxc6 Bh3 12. Re1 Rc8 13.
Bf3 Qa5 14. Qd2 Rfd8 {with perfect mobilization and full compensation for the
pawn, Zablotsky,S (2451)-Shomoev,A (2486) Novosibirsk 2003 (1-0, 32)}) 10...
Be6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Ne5 Nd5 13. Bd2 {Panning c3-c4.} cxd4 $5 $146 14. Nxc6 (
14. cxd4 Rc8 {planning ...c6-c5.}) 14... Qd7 15. Nxd4 Rac8 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 $11 {
Black will soon retrieve the c3-pawn (or, at White's choice, the a2-pawn).}) (
9. Bb2 {is an increasingly popular move. White prepares the central expansion
with e2-e4 by overdefending d4.} Nc6 10. Re1 Nd5 11. e4 (11. Nc4 Nb6 $11) 11...
Nb6 12. Rb1 (12. d5 Na5 13. Rb1 Nac4 14. Nxc4 Nxc4 15. Ba1 e6 16. Bf1 exd5 17.
exd5 Nd6 {ith such perfect blockade and the inevitable exchange of the
dark-squared bishops Black cannot have any problems.} 18. c4 Bg4 19. Qb3 Bxa1
20. Rxa1 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 Re8 $11 {Bellia,F (2452)-Valsecchi,A (2466) Milan 2015 
(½-½, 45)}) (12. h3 Na5 13. Rb1 {In Efimenko,Z (2655)-Salem,A (2608) Warsaw
2016 (½-½, 45) Black played too provocatively 13...Be6 14.d5 Bd7, basically
wasting a tempo. Stronger is} Bd7 {with several deas, such as ...Qc8, ...Na4
or ...Ba4.} 14. d5 {Otherwise Black may play ...e7-e6, slowing down the
central expansion.} Nac4 15. Nxc4 Nxc4 16. Ba1 Qc8 17. Kh2 e6 18. Nd2 Nxd2 19.
Qxd2 c4 $11 {With interesting play and mutual cances.}) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Bg4
14. d5 Bxb2 15. Rxb2 Ne5 16. Qb3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nxf3+ 18. Qxf3 Rc8 19. h4 {
Giri,A (2776)-Grandelius,N (2573) Doha 2014 (1-0, 74)} Qd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7h3,
Gf7f5,Gc8c5,Gf8c8] This looks like the most consistent move, with such ideas
as ...Qh3 (especially after h4-h5), ...Rc5 and ...Rfc8, or simply ...f7-f5.}) (
9. Qb3 {fails preventing the bishop's development:} Nc6 10. Rd1 Be6 11. Qxb7
Bd5 12. Qb2 $146 {Curiously, so far White has not thought of retreating with
the queen from the threatened square.} (12. dxc5 {Fries Nielsen,J (2395)
-Zezulkin,J (2440) Norresundby 1992 (½-½, 14)} Ne4 13. Rxd5 Qxd5 14. Nd2 f5
15. Nxe4 fxe4 $15) (12. Bf4 Nxd4 13. Qa6 Qb6 14. Qd3 Be4 15. Qc4 Bd5 16. Qd3
Ne6 $15 {Dang,H (2043)-Nguyen,D (2496) Ho Chi Minh City 2014 (0-1, 83)}) 12...
Rb8 $44 {Black will gain several tempi due to the exposed position of the
enemy queen.} 13. Qc2 Be4 14. Qa4 Nd5 15. Bd2 cxd4 16. Nxd4 (16. Qxc6 dxc3 17.
Be1 c2 18. Nxc2 Rc8 $11) 16... Nxd4 17. cxd4 Nb6 18. Qa6 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qxd4 20.
Bf4 Qe4+ 21. f3 Qb7 22. Qxb7 Rxb7 23. Rab1 Rc8 $11) (9. Rb1 {is an atempt at
causing Black problems with developing his bishop.} Nc6 10. Ne5 cxd4 $1 {
Forcing White releasing the tension and thus enabling ...Bf5.} 11. Nxc6 bxc6
12. cxd4 Bf5 13. Rb7 Ne4 14. e3 Nd6 15. Rb4 Rc8 {The break with ...c6-c5 is
ensured after which Black will keep active play, Ponkratov,P (2605)-Cheparinov,
I (2678) Khanty-Mansiysk 2013 (0-1, 44)}) (9. Nc4 Nc6 10. Nce5 ({Most games
continue with} 10. Nfe5 {but this transposes to 9.Ne5.}) (10. Ba3 Be6 11. Nce5
Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Nd5 {Black already has excellent counterplay, planning ...Qa5.}
13. Bxc5 $6 Rc8 14. c4 Nc3 15. Qc2 Bxe5 16. Qxc3 Rxc5 17. dxe5 Qc7 $15 {
Espig,L (2440)-Mohr,S (2430) Germany 1991 (½-½, 31)}) 10... Nxe5 11. Nxe5 (
11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Ne4 13. Bb2 f5 14. c4 Be6) 11... Nd5 12. Bb2 Nb6) 9...
Nc6 10. Qe2 Bf5 11. Bb2 (11. Rd1 Qb6 {transposes below.}) 11... Qb6 ({The move
order based on ...Bf5 was initially designed by Kasparov for his matches with
Karpov as a way of creating the threat} 11... e5 {But there is no need to
expose himself to} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Bd3 14. Qe1 Nd7 15. f4 Bxf1 16. Qxf1
{with great compensation for the exchange. Black can play normal developing
moves, increasing the pressure against the enemy center.}) 12. Rfd1 (12. d5 Na5
$146 13. c4 Qb4 {Threatening ...Nxd5.} 14. Nh4 Be4 15. Bxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxg7 Kxg7
17. Qd3 f5 18. Rac1 Rad8 19. f3 Nd6 20. f4 e6 $11) (12. Rfc1 Rfd8 13. Nc4 Qa6
14. Bf1 Rac8 15. a4 Ne4 $146 16. Qd1 Na5 $15 {With very active play.}) 12...
Rfd8 13. Nc4 Qa6 14. Bf1 Rac8 15. a4 Na5 16. Nxa5 (16. Nfe5 cxd4 17. cxd4 Nxc4
18. Nxc4 Bg4 19. f3 Be6 20. Rdc1 Bh6 $15 {Ponfilenok,V (2440)-Iordachescu,V 
(2607) St Petersburg 2009 (0-1, 71)}) 16... Qxa5 17. Qb5 Qc7 18. Rdc1 Ne4 {
With at least equal play, Georgiev,K (2654)-Areshchenko,A (2570) Coventry 2005
(½-½, 40)} *

