1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. f3 {This is a clear invitation to the Saemisch King's
Indian.} Nc6 $5 {This unusual move only apparently cooperates to White's plan.
Due to the weird move order, delaying the knight development, White will not
reach a genuine Saemisch, even though play usually takes King's Indian
contours.} ({As an experienced Benoni player, I would also consider} 3... c5 {
, but this would lead to a genuine Benoni after} 4. d5 {This position may be
examined in another series of articles, but not on the Grunfeld.}) ({The main
line goes} 3... d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Be3 {Black has managed
to keep the Grunfeld character of the play, but he was denied the right of
exchanging on c3. I find the resulting positions hard to analyze and their
forced character hardly suits the "positional repertoire" built up here.}) 4.
d5 (4. Nc3 d5 {leads to similar structures as in the lines examined in the Bc4
Exchange system with the difference that White has played f2-f3 earlier than
usual:} 5. cxd5 ({Or if} 5. e4 dxe4 6. d5 Ne5 7. fxe4 Bg7 8. Nf3 Nxf3+ 9. gxf3
O-O 10. Be3 e6 11. Qd2 exd5 12. cxd5 c6 13. dxc6 Qe7 14. O-O-O bxc6 15. Qd6 {
Vallejo Pons,F (2684)-Swiercz,D (2620) Berlin 2015 (0-1, 66)} Qb7 $5 $132) 5...
Nxd5 6. e4 Nxc3 7. bxc3 e5 8. Bb5 (8. d5 {releases the tension too easily:} Na5
9. Be3 c6 {it is useful to keep the bishop on its initial diagonal, for if
c3-c4 Black could consider ...Bb4+.} 10. dxc6 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 bxc6 12. Ne2 Nc4
13. Bg5 Be7 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. Nd4 Na5 16. Nc2 Be6 $15 {Charkhalashvili,I (2329)
-Sutovsky,E (2622) Tbilisi 2016 (0-1, 55)}) 8... Bd7 9. Ne2 Bg7 10. Be3 O-O 11.
d5 ({Justified by the fact that} 11. O-O $2 {allows} Nxd4 $1 {winning a pawn
since} 12. Nxd4 $2 {only makes things worse:} exd4 13. Bxd7 dxe3 $19) 11... Na5
12. Bd3 b6 13. O-O {Anand,V (2791)-Carlsen,M (2776) Linares 2009 (½-½, 29)}
f5 $5 $132) (4. e4 {fails stabilizing the position according to Saemisch
standards due to} e5 $1 5. dxe5 (5. d5 Nd4 {ensures Black an outpost on d4.
The fact that the d-pawn has not moved is useful after} 6. Ne2 c5 $11 7. dxc6
$2 dxc6 $1 $15) (5. Ne2 exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 {In this line, too, Black benefits
from delaying ...d7-d6:} 7. Nxc6 (7. Be3 $2 {runs into} Nxe4 $1 $17 {winning a
pawn. The point is that in all lines, if White moves with his knight, the
a1-rook would be lost.} 8. fxe4 $2 Qh4+ $1 $19) 7... bxc6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Be2 d5
$1 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. exd5 Bb7 12. O-O Nxd5 13. Ne4 c5 $15 {Bercys,S (2434)
-Shabalov,A (2580) ICC INT 2009 (1-0, 60)}) 5... Nxe5 6. Be3 Bg7 7. Nc3 {
reaches some sort of Saemisch structure but in a very active version for Black
as instead of ...exd4 the tension was released with dxe5.} d6 8. Nge2 O-O 9.
Nf4 (9. Nd4 {allows the central plan:} c6 10. Be2 d5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. exd5
Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 $11 {Ducas, J-Najdorf, M Sao Paulo 1957 (½-½, 41) Of
course there were some newer games, too with this central break, but I chose
the classical to prove that people knew one or two things in the past, too.})
9... c6 10. h4 ({Not a purely attacking move. In fact, more of a defensive
one! The careless} 10. Be2 {allows} g5 11. Nh3 Bxh3 12. gxh3 Nh5 13. Rg1 Nf4
$15 {Serov,M (2375)-Melkumyan,H (2614) St Petersburg 2010 (0-1, 26)}) 10... a6
{Since ...d6-d5 is not available Black prepares the wing break, taking
advantage of the fact that the c6-pawn is not hanging to a d4-knight and that
the e5-knight is stable.} 11. Be2 (11. h5 b5 12. c5 {1-0 (40) Cmilyte,V (2467)
-Andreasen,P (2244) Copenhagen 2007} d5 13. exd5 b4 14. Na4 g5 $17) 11... b5
12. c5 {Krasenkow,M (2647)-Stryjecki,M (2423) Warsaw 2006 (1-0, 53)} Ne8 $5 13.
Qd2 (13. Qc2 Qe7 14. cxd6 Nxd6 15. Bc5 Nd7 {with perfect regrouping.}) 13...
Ra7 $5 14. O-O-O Rd7 $132) 4... Ne5 5. e4 d6 6. Nc3 (6. Ne2 {leads to a
slightly different knights placement, but tends to leave White underdeveloped.}
Bg7 7. Nec3 O-O 8. Be2 e6 9. f4 (9. O-O exd5 10. cxd5 c6 11. dxc6 bxc6 12. Be3
Re8 13. Nd2 d5 {with excellent counterplay in the centre in Mamedyarov,S (2719)
-Carlsen,M (2801) Moscow (blitz) 2009 (0-1, 29)}) 9... Ned7 10. O-O exd5 11.
cxd5 Re8 12. Bf3 Nc5 13. Re1 {Nakamura,H (2710)-Svidler,P (2739) Amsterdam
2009 (0-1, 32)} c6 $15) 6... Bg7 {The position only looks similar to the
Saemisch attack. Due to the early central operations, White does not find it
easy to develop his kingside. The next move is more or less forced, but it
slightly weakens the center offering Black chances for counterplay.} 7. f4 ({
White has no other way of developing his king's knight. For instance, after} 7.
Be2 O-O {he would have to transpose below with} 8. f4 {anyway.}) 7... Ned7 8.
Nf3 ({The alternative is} 8. Nh3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc5 10. Nf2 e5 $1 ({This is the
fifth way of attacking the center, taking advantage of the fact that White's
knights are far from the e5-square. If} 10... e6 11. O-O exd5 12. cxd5 Re8 13.
Bf3 $14) 11. dxe6 (11. fxe5 Ne8 $1 12. exd6 Nxd6 {Black has a wonderful knight
placement and enough compensation for the pawn.} 13. O-O Qh4 14. g3 Qe7 15. Bf4
Ncxe4 16. Ncxe4 Nxe4 17. Bf3 Nxf2 18. Rxf2 Qc5 $11 {Laznicka,V (2679)-Salgado
Lopez,I (2622) Dubai 2014 (0-1, 32)}) 11... fxe6 12. Be3 b6 13. Qc2 Bb7 14.
O-O-O Nfd7 15. Bf3 {Wojtaszek,R (2734)-Baron,T (2541) Skopje 2015 (1-0, 33)}
Bxc3 $5 {Preparing a blockade without a bad bishop behind the pawns.} 16. Qxc3
e5 17. h4 (17. Ng4 Qe7) 17... exf4 18. Bd4 Qe7 19. h5 g5 20. Ng4 Ne5 {White
needs finding something to compensate for Black's stability on dark squares.}
21. Bxe5 (21. Nxe5 $2 dxe5 22. Bxe5 Rae8 23. Bh8 h6 $17 {[%csl Ge4,Gh8]}) 21...
dxe5 22. b4 Nxe4 23. Qd3 Rad8 24. Nh6+ Kg7 25. Nf5+ Rxf5 26. h6+ Kf6 27. Qxd8
Qxd8 28. Rxd8 Ng3 29. Rf8+ Kg6 30. Rg8+ Kf6 $11 31. Rd1 Bxf3 32. gxf3 e4 $36)
8... O-O 9. Bd3 (9. Be2 {faces White with the risk of his centre getting
over-extended:} Nc5 10. e5 Nfe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. O-O (12. Qd4 f5 13. O-O e6
$132) 12... c6 13. Be3 {Stojanovic,M (2574)-Popovic,A (2324) Valjevo 2011 (1-0,
27)} Bf5 $1 {Taking measures against the threatened Bd3.} 14. Rc1 (14. Bd3 $2
cxd5 15. cxd5 dxe5 16. fxe5 Qxd5 $17) 14... Rc8 $13 15. Nh4 $6 e6 $1 16. Nxf5
exf5 {White's centre is obviously hanging.}) 9... c6 10. O-O cxd5 11. cxd5 (11.
exd5 $146 Qb6+ 12. Kh1 Nc5 13. Bc2 e6 $36) 11... b5 {With just enough
counterplay.} 12. h3 (12. a3 Nc5 13. Bc2 Bb7 14. Be3 a5 15. Bxc5 dxc5 16. Nxb5
{Yang,D (2485)-Bora,S (2195) Wheeling 2013 (1-0, 37)} Qb8 $1 {Targetting f4
and the b5-knight.} 17. Nd2 Bxd5 $11) (12. Qe2 b4 13. Na4 Qa5 $15 {Popov,M 
(2256)-Shinkevich,V (2484) Izhevsk 2014 (0-1, 40)}) 12... Nc5 13. a3 Bb7 $1
$146 {Aiming for rapid counterplay in the centre.} (13... a5 14. Be3 Nxd3 15.
Qxd3 $16 {Gunina,V (2497)-Muzychuk,A (2555) Batumi 2016 (1-0, 42)}) 14. Be3 e6
{White cannot keep his space advantage intact and the position becomes messy.}
