1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 {One of the main issues in the Gruenfeld is that
White has an enormous choice of systems at his disposal. Not all of them are
challenging, not all of them popular, but these are subjective thoughts, of
course. Due to space limitation, I have included in this last game of the
whole article series brief guidelines to lines I (possibly subjectively)
considered not topical.} 4. e3 {This can lead to a wide range of variations.} (
4. Qb3 dxc4 5. Qxc4 Bg7 6. e4 O-O {has independent value only if White delays
his king's knight's development, otherwise the game would transpose to the
Russian system, 5.Qb3. But with the knight on g1 White is exposed to ...f7-f5.}
7. Be2 Nfd7 8. Be3 Nb6 9. Qd3 (9. Qc5 f5 10. Nh3 fxe4 11. Ng5 Rf5 12. Qb4 e6 {
Defending the a2-g8 diagonal.} 13. Ngxe4 (13. Ncxe4 Nd5 14. Qb3 Nxe3 15. Qxe3 {
Sodoma,J (2380)-Navara,D (2722) Czechia 2012 (0-1, 35)} Nc6 $17) 13... Nc6 14.
Qb3 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bxd4 16. O-O-O c5 17. h4 Bd7 18. h5 g5 $13) 9... f5 10. Rd1
f4 11. Bc1 Nc6 12. Nf3 Bg4 13. e5 e6 14. O-O (14. h3 Bf5 15. Qd2 {Troff,K 
(2459)-Chirila,I (2521) Dallas 2014 (1-0, 33)} g5 $11) 14... Qe7 15. h3 Bf5 16.
Qb5 {Sadzikowski,D (2388)-Kolosowski,M (2408) Polanica Zdroj 2011 (½-½, 52)}
a6 17. Qb3 (17. Qc5 Qxc5 18. dxc5 Nd5 19. Nxd5 exd5 20. Rxd5 Be6 $11) 17... Na5
18. Qa3 Qxa3 19. bxa3 Nc6 20. Bxf4 Bc2 21. Rd2 Rxf4 22. Rxc2 Nxd4 23. Nxd4 Rxd4
$11) (4. Qa4+ Bd7 5. Qb3 {has similar ideas, but the move ...Bd7 is useful in
many situations, and not misplaced as White would wish proving.} dxc4 6. Qxc4 (
6. Qxb7 $2 Nc6 {endangers the queen and the... a1-rook!} 7. Bf4 e5 8. dxe5 Rb8
9. Qa6 Nh5 10. Bd2 Nb4 11. Qxc4 Nc2+) 6... Bg7 7. e4 O-O 8. e5 (8. Be3 Ng4 $11)
(8. Be2 b5 $1 $36 {Here is where the bishop proves useful}) ({If} 8. Nf3 {
Black has a choice between 8...Bg4 transposing to 5.Qb3 and} b5) 8... Be6 9.
exf6 {The critical continuation.} (9. Qb5 Nd5 $15 10. Qxb7 $6 Nb6 {Threatening
to trap the queen with ...c7-c6 and ...Bc8.} 11. Qe4 Bf5 12. Qh4 Nc6 $17 {
with great advance indevelopment and overwhelming initiative. Chekhov,V (2440)
-Schmidt,W (2475) Polanica Zdroj 1981 (0-1, 32)}) 9... Bxc4 10. fxg7 Kxg7 11.
Bxc4 Qxd4 {White's position is optically pleasant, but Black has a material
advantage and no real weaknesses after all.} 12. Be2 Nc6 13. Nf3 Qb6 14. O-O
Rad8 15. Rb1 e5 16. Re1 a6 17. b4 Rfe8 18. Bf1 f6 19. Na4 Qa7 20. Nc5 a5 21.
Be3 b6 22. Bb5 {Lev,R (2457)-Huzman,A (2575) Israel 1999 (½-½, 22)} Nxb4 23.
Bxe8 Rxe8 24. Ne4 Qa8 25. Nc3 Qc6 $17) (4. h4 {enjoys some popularity lately.}
c6 {Overdefending d5 in order to stop h4-h5.} 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. Bg5 (6. cxd5 cxd5
7. Bf4 {leads to a version of the exchange Slav where White does not find it
easy justifying h2-h4.} Nc6 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 Bg4 10. O-O Rc8 11. Ne5 Bxe2 12.
Qxe2 e6 13. Nd3 Nd7 14. h5 a6 15. Rac1 Qe7 16. hxg6 $11 {½-½ Morozevich,A 
(2719)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2735) Poikovsky 2014}) 6... Ne4 7. e3 Qa5 {This is
similar with our lines against Bg5. The slightly different circumstances are
at least no problem for Black.} 8. Qb3 dxc4 (8... Nd7 {is an alternative, too:}
9. Rc1 Nxg5 10. hxg5 dxc4 11. Bxc4 O-O {followed by ...Nb6.}) 9. Bxc4 Nd6 10.
Be2 Be6 11. Qc2 h6 12. Bf4 Nd7 {with a familiar picture.}) 4... Bg7 5. Nf3 (5.
cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. Ne2 {is probably the newest variation, invented by
Portisch during his work as Karpov's second to the last match with Kasparov.
Karpov did not decide trying it out, so Portisch himself introduced it much
later into practice. Black is under no immediate pressure, and the main events
are taking place in the middlegame.} O-O 8. Nc3 Qd6 9. Be2 c6 10. O-O Nd7 11.
Ne4 (11. Qc2 e5 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. e4 Nf6 14. Be3 Ng4 15. Bxg4 Bxg4 16. h3 {
Kramnik,V (2790)-Svidler,P (2750) Nice 2010 (1/2, 31)} Be6 $5 17. Rfd1 Qa5 $11
{Krasenkow}) (11. b3 Rd8 $5 12. Bb2 Nb6 13. Ne4 Qc7 14. Qc1 Bf5 15. Nc5 Nd7 $11
{Kunte,A (2517)-Gopal,G (2609) New Delhi 2010 (1/2, 26)}) 11... Qc7 12. Bd2 Nf6
({More restrictive than} 12... Nb6 13. f4 $5 {and Black did not find it easy
to break the enemy centre, Andreikin,D (2727)-Caruana,F (2796) Dortmund 2013 
(0-1, 43)}) 13. Nxf6+ (13. Nc5 Rd8 14. f4 $6 b6 15. Nd3 c5 $36) 13... Bxf6 14.
Bc3 (14. Qc2 Rd8 15. Bf3 Bf5 16. e4 Be6 17. d5 Bd7 $11 {Siebrecht,S (2496)
-Nyback,T (2599) Germany 2014 (0-1, 50)}) ({Without knights on board} 14. f4 {
is less threatening:} Be6 15. Rc1 Rfd8 16. Qc2 $6 Qb6 {White already needs
considering the threats ...Bxd4 and ...Bxa2.}) 14... e5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Bxe5
Qxe5 17. Qb3 Qe7 {½-½ De Jong,J (2444)-Huzman,A (2605) Plovdiv 2010}) (5. Qb3
{is a slightly different version of 6.Qb3 below, to which it can transpose.
But play can become independent if after} e6 {White plays} 6. Qa3 {preventing
castling. Still, Black can slowly deal with this problem, as the queen does
not stand especially well on a3:} a5 7. Nf3 c6 8. b3 Na6 9. Bd2 Nb4 10. Qb2 {
In several games, Black has castled, which looks quite all right, but} c5 $5
$146 {makes sense, preparing to meet a2-a3 with ...Nc6. The queen apparently
does not stand well on the long diagonal, and the d2-bishop could also have
hoped for better.}) 5... O-O 6. cxd5 {Just one of a long series of move tried
here.} (6. Be2 {is inoffensive, leading to some sort of reversed Catalan, or
Tarrasch, with pleasant play for Black.} c5 7. O-O (7. dxc5 dxc4 8. O-O Qa5 9.
Bxc4 Qxc5 10. Bb3 Nc6 11. e4 Bg4 12. Be3 Qa5 13. h3 Rad8 14. Qe2 Bxf3 15. Qxf3
Nd7 16. Rfd1 e6 17. Qe2 {½-½ Fressinet,L (2697)-Dorfman,J (2583) Belfort 2010
} Nc5 $15) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 (8. Nxd4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 10. a4 Qc7 11. Qe2 Rd8
12. f3 Nbd7 13. Ba2 Nb6 14. Rd1 Nfd5 $36 {Barcza,G-Kortschnoj,V Stockholm 1962
(0-1, 60)}) 8... Nc6 9. h3 $5 ({It is not simple to use the extra tempo on the
Tarrasch Defence. Anyway, we are not talking about an aggressive opening, but
just one trying to hold the Isolated pawn. If} 9. Re1 Bg4 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. h3
Be6 12. Bf1 Rc8 {Black has comfortable play. The extra tempo Bf1 is no big
shakes.}) 9... Bf5 10. cxd5 (10. Be3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Rc8 12. Be2 Be6 13. Qd2 Qa5
14. Bh6 Rfd8 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Rfd1 Rd6 17. Qe3 Rcd8 $15 {Bisguier,A (2430)
-Karpov,A (2630) Skopje 1972 (0-1, 32)}) 10... Nxd5 11. Qb3 Be6 12. Qxb7 $6
Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. Bh6 Rb8 15. Qa6 Rxb2 16. Nxd5 Qxd5 17. Bxf8 Kxf8 18. a4
Rb3 19. Rad1 Rg3 {0-1 Bareev,E (2680)-Kasparov,G (2770) Paris (rapid) 1991}) (
6. Bd3 {is likely to transpose to 6.Be2 as after} c5 7. O-O $6 cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6
{the bishop stands worse on d3 than on e2.}) (6. Bd2 {is meant to prevent . ..
Qa5 after} c5 7. dxc5 {but Black has other ways of retrieving the pawn, even
though the process is longer:} Na6 8. cxd5 Nxc5 9. Bc4 {This is also typical
for the Catalan, with reversed colours, of course.} a6 10. a4 (10. b4 Nce4 11.
Rc1 b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 13. O-O Qd6 14. a3 Rfd8 $11 {Marovic,D-Tukmakov,V Zagreb
1971 (½-½, 22)}) 10... Bf5 11. O-O Rc8 12. Qe2 Nfe4 13. Nd4 (13. Rfd1 Nxc3
14. Bxc3 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Ne4 16. Rd4 Qa5 17. Qb2 Qxc3 18. Qxc3 Nxc3 19. Nd2 Rfd8
$15 {Pachman,L-Shamkovich,L Sarajevo 1963 (½-½, 41)}) (13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Bb4
Bxd5 15. Rfd1 Qb6 16. Bxc5 Bxc4 17. Bxb6 Bxe2 18. Rd2 Bc4 $11 {Efimov,I (2480)
-Stangl,M (2494) Laveno 2003 (½-½, 25)}) (13. Rac1 Nd6 $15) 13... Nxd2 14.
Qxd2 Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Qb4 Bxd4 17. exd4 Bxd5 $15 {Sahovic,D (2520)
-Liberzon,V (2515) Lone Pine 1979 (0-1, 49)}) (6. Qb3 {forces Black taking a
decision, but the queen is exposed on b3.} e6 {The good old antidote. Black
switched to the slow mode, heading for a structure with a double fianchetto
and possibly hanging pawns..} 7. Bd2 b6 8. Rc1 (8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O Nbd7 10. c5
$6 Ne4 11. Be1 e5 $36 {Shamaev,L-Kortschnoj,V Leningrad 1953 (0-1, 40)}) 8...
Bb7 9. Be2 (9. cxd5 exd5 10. Be2 c6 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Rfd1 Re8 13. Be1 Bf8 14.
Nd2 Re6 15. Bf3 $11 {Gligoric,S-Botvinnik,M Moscow 1947 (½-½, 41)}) 9... Nbd7
(9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nbd7 11. O-O c5 12. Be2 Qb8 13. h3 Rd8 14. Rfd1 cxd4 15.
Nxd4 Nc5 16. Qc2 Qe5 17. Be1 Rac8 $11 {Vertetics,A (2416)-Mamedyarov,S (2766)
chess.com INT 2017 (0-1, 46)}) 10. O-O Ne4 (10... c5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. dxc5
Nxc5 13. Qa3 {Black has an active version of the isolani, with the d2-bishop
and the white queen far from optimally placed.} Nfe4 14. Rfd1 Qf6 15. Be1 Rfd8
16. b4 Ne6 17. Nb5 Qe7 $11 {Nikolic,S (2372)-Jansa,V (2466) Germany 2001 (0-1,
56)}) 11. Rfd1 dxc4 12. Qxc4 Nd6 13. Qb3 c5 $11 {Polugaevsky,L-Kortschnoj,V
Riga 1958 (½-½, 41)}) (6. b4 {is the so-called Makogonov variation. It can
be answered in more than one way. Here is just a simple one:} Ne4 7. Bb2 (7.
Nxe4 dxe4 8. Nd2 f5 9. Be2 a5 10. b5 c5 11. bxc6 bxc6 $132) (7. Nxd5 c6 8. Nf4
e5 $17 {Poliakov,V (2375)-Kuzmin,G (2429) Lugansk 2010 (0-1, 20) The hanging
fork on f2 prevents the captures on e5.}) 7... c6 8. Bd3 Nxc3 9. Bxc3 dxc4 10.
Bxc4 Nd7 11. O-O Nb6 12. Bb3 Qd6 13. Rc1 Bg4 14. h3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Nd5 16. Bxd5
cxd5 $11 {Kholmov,R-Kortschnoj,V Kiev 1954 (½-½, 29)}) 6... Nxd5 7. Bc4 {
Trying to get some sort of exchange variation with a well defended d4-pawn.} (
7. Qb3 {is less popular:} Nb6 8. Be2 Be6 9. Qc2 (9. Qa3 Bc4 10. O-O Bxe2 11.
Nxe2 Nc6 $11) (9. Qd1 c5 10. O-O Nc6 11. dxc5 Nd7 $11) 9... Bf5 10. Qd1 c5 11.
O-O cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd7 13. e4 Nc6 14. Be3 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bc6 $11 {Serper,G (2420)
-Kalinitschew,S (2455) Novosibirsk 1989 (½-½, 57)}) 7... Nb6 ({There is
nothing wrong with} 7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 c5 {but the main move offers White even
fewer chances for anything concrete.}) 8. Bb3 c5 {The position will soon turn
similar to those after 6.Be2} 9. O-O (9. dxc5 N6d7 10. Na4 Na6 11. c6 bxc6 12.
O-O Ndc5 $36) (9. d5 c4 10. Bc2 Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qxd5 12. Ba3 Nc6 $17 {Drogou,G 
